{"name":"Ship Entertainment","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_2fzh7f9etq5","path":"Seas of Eberron#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Ship Entertainment</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>With time on their hands and precious few places to go, sailors and pirates have come up with an astonishing array of pastimes.</p>\n<h3>Songs and Stories</h3>\n<p>One way sailors amuse themselves is through songs and stories. Sailors love a good sea chantey, and characters with @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} quickly find themselves popular members of the crew. If a character succeeds at a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} check, he gains a +1 bonus per @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise} to social checks made to interact with any listener among the crew for the next 24 hours, up to a maximum of +4. A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure}, however, indicates that the next time he attempts to use @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} to entertain the crew, everyone ignores him.</p>\n<h3>Gambling Games</h3>\n<p>Other recreations have two things in common: they are dangerous, and they are played for money. When betting on any of the following games, the minimum bet is 1 gp, and the maximum ready cash any sailor in the lesser crew is likely to have is 20 gp. Some people are bad losers&mdash;the ramifications of this are left for the GM to decide.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Arm Wrestling:</strong> Not merely typical arm wrestling bouts, such matches are usually conducted on a barrel top covered in broken glass, knives, or caltrops. Participants make opposed @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} checks, with the higher result determining the winner, and the loser taking an level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises} as his hand and arm are pushed onto whatever lies on the table.</li>\n<li><strong>Hog Lob: </strong>Participants lob a lead ingot covered in a greased piglet skin, the &ldquo;hog,&rdquo; as far across the deck as possible. This game is resolved by @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} checks between any number of players, who agree on a bet beforehand. The hog counts as an @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Improvised Weapons]{improvised weapon}. Some pirates claim to have participated in games played against Devourer using a live hog.</li>\n<li><strong>Heave:</strong> This potentially deadly drinking game is played with rum and takes place between any number of pirates, who bet to predict the winner beforehand. Each pirate drinks a half pint of rum in one swig. Doing so forces participants to make a successful @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} check &ndash;1 or take a level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. This check increases by &ndash;1 for each consecutive drink. Pirates then take turns drinking until only one is left standing. Some tales tell of entire crews drinking themselves to death through this game, leaving ships of drunk ghosts wandering the shipping routes.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"9VlOO3cACSA2vHNI"}
{"name":"Crew of the Wormwood","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_2fzh7f9etq5","path":"Seas of Eberron#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Crew of the Wormwood</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<h2>Officers</h2>\n<h3>Captain Berrigan Redeker</h3>\n<h3>First Mate Mister Dabrak</h3>\n<p>Mr. Dabrak is the <em>Wormwood&rsquo;s</em> bullying and sadistic first mate. He is Captain Redeker&rsquo;s second-in-command, and his word is law on deck. He takes an immediate dislike to the PCs and any friends they make among the crew. Dabrak is terrified of Captain Redeker, however, and has more things on his mind than just the PCs. He&rsquo;s suspicious of everyone on the crew, and while he grows to hate the PCs, he does not sully his hands with fighting them unless they attack him, in which case he fights with relish, calling on his allies for aid in dealing with the &ldquo;mutineers.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>Dabrak is a figure to be hated, though the PCs have little opportunity to get their revenge at first. By the end of the adventure, however, the PCs finally have the opportunity to give him (and his toady, Master Scourge) their just rewards.</p>\n<h3>Master Scourge</h3>\n<p>Master Scourge is the Wormwood&rsquo;s boatswain and masterat-arms, and Mr. Plugg&rsquo;s right-hand man. As boatswain, he is in charge of all activities and sailors on deck, and as master-at-arms, he is responsible for discipline. Master Scourge is a sneering man with a braided beard and a mouth full of gold teeth. His body is tall and thin, and even his long coat and heavy boots fail to give any impression of strength or bulk. A sadistic coward, Scourge uses his association with Plugg as protection and in return has no morals when it comes to the tasks his master sets. He is bold and violent when the odds are stacked in his favor, happily kicking a dying dog in the street if asked to do so. But should that dog get up and bite, he quickly f lees.</p>\n<p>Master Scourge is a key villain in the early part of the adventure, and his whispered words further poison Mr. Plugg against the PCs. Scourge&rsquo;s relationship with the PCs is a crucial one. He immediately senses something out of the ordinary about them, and his dreams of rank and fortune soon begin to unravel. Like most bullies, Scourge is a coward at heart, and sets out to discredit and ultimately kill his rivals.</p>\n<p>This enmity is personal, and primarily directed at a single PC, though how this manifests is ultimately up to you. Scourge was recently rejected by Sandara Quinn (see page 56), and any object of her affections is sure to earn his jealousy and hatred. Likewise, Scourge might be jealous of a handsome and talented PC and fear for his own position on the ship. While Scourge focuses his hostility on one PC, he is also happy to intimidate and victimize the other PCs, as well as seeking to discredit the PCs&rsquo; friends. He avoids the PCs as a group, however, and immediately goes to Plugg&rsquo;s side if threatened. If actually attacked, he also goes to Plugg, who may have the PCs disciplined.</p>\n<p>Playing the bully requires you to temper the PCs&rsquo; anger while ensuring they recognize Scourge as a deadly enemy with far too many allies to simply be killed. Terrified as he is of Harrigan and having no desire to be keelhauled, Scourge won&rsquo;t try to kill the PCs&mdash;at least, not at first. Instead, he seeks to poison the other crew members against the PCs, and is likely to succeed with his own small band of admirers, whom the PCs will find hard to convert. In essence, this group becomes a rival adventuring party, but with one crucial difference: these rivals also enjoy the support of Mr. Plugg. It&rsquo;s not until events move on to the Man&rsquo;s Promise in Part Two that Plugg and Scourge decide to have done with the PCs, but they&rsquo;ll eventually get their comeuppance at the hands of the PCs in Part Three</p>\n<h3>Ambrose \"Fishguts\" Kroop</h3>\n<p>Ambrose Kroop is the ship&rsquo;s cook, nicknamed &ldquo;Fishguts&rdquo; by the crew, though whether this refers to the contents of his soups or the stains on his apron is unclear. His job is to bring the ship&rsquo;s biscuit on deck at dawn for the crew, and prepare and serve the evening meal. Kroop is a drunkard, but not constantly inebriated, and is a potential ally for the PCs. His unpredictability makes him a frustrating but ultimately useful friend. Like his friend Cut-Throat Grok, Kroop is from the school of hard knocks, but where Grok has become tough, Kroop has capitulated in the face of endless discipline and violence. However, as the adventure progresses and he becomes closer to the PCs, he becomes an increasingly useful ally.</p>\n<p>While Kroop is indifferent to the PCs at the beginning of the adventure, he is, at heart, a friendly salt, and soon becomes attached to any character who makes a modicum of effort as the cook&rsquo;s mate. In general, Kroop likes to cook and drink rum. He is usually insensibly drunk in his quarters during the evening, rarely venturing onto deck after serving the evening meal. Kroop&rsquo;s cook&rsquo;s mate gains a +2 bonus on all checks to inf luence the quartermaster Cut-Throat Grok. Kroop is also happy to lend his mate any equipment from the galley, though stealing it without his permission is easy enough.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"FJHhcYei8MYZlo2y"}
{"name":"Theft, Pilfering, and Secrecy","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_2fzh7f9etq5","path":"Seas of Eberron#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Theft, Pilfering, and Secrecy</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The <em>Wormwood </em>is a pirate ship, filled with dubious and murderous characters at best. Theft is common, but the key is not getting caught.</p>\n<p>To perform any action unobserved on a crowded ship use the following guidelines for modifiers to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} rolls.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li>Attempting a stealthy action in a crowd, such as casting a spell with verbal or somatic components without being noticed: &ndash;3 penalty to the roll.</li>\n<li>Attempting a stealthy action where there is a chance of discovery, such as visiting the quartermaster&rsquo;s store during work, exploring a room during the day, or attempting to open a chest in a room while its occupants are sleeping: &ndash;2 penalty to the roll.</li>\n<li>Attempting a stealthy action under cover of a suitable diversion, such as attempting to open lockers when the rest of the crew are working or on deck enjoying themselves: no modifier.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Failure</h3>\n<p>Failing this check means the character attempting the action is merely disturbed and is unable to complete the action. A Critical Failure on the checkthe character is caught red-handed by a random crew member, and might be turned over to Master Scourge for discipline.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"Fo0Hd3YInpT7c50D"}
{"name":"Ship Board Entertainment","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_2fzh7f9etq5","path":"Seas of Eberron#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Ship Board Entertainment</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>In addition to their normal jobs on the ship, the PCs can also utilize their time during the day (and night) to explore the ship, scrounger for gear, interact with their shipmates, or attempt to inf luence NPCs.</p>\n<p>With the PCs potentially scattered across the ship working at their jobs, however, there is a danger that early events in the adventure might focus too much upon the actions of individual characters. Some PCs might have more time on their hands and act accordingly. To avoid this, the PCs&rsquo; activities aboard ship&mdash;carrying out their assigned tasks; exploring the ship; robbing, bullying, or befriending shipmates; working; or playing&mdash;are performed as part of ship actions. These actions ref lect the time required to set up or complete an activity, such as gathering enough crew to play a game, scouting out a room to make sure it&rsquo;s empty, and so on. Remember that even the cook&rsquo;s mate has a job to do during the day, and ship actions are meant to ref lect the available time a PC can carve out from his or her work time without going into too much detail.</p>\n<p>Each PC can normally take two ship actions each day, one during the day and one at night. A PC can also attempt to take up to two additional ship actions during the middle watch in the dead of night (any nighttime ship action marked with an asterisk), but to do so the PC must make a successful Constitution check (DC 10, +4 per extra ship action taken) or be fatigued for the next day.</p>\n<p>A list of possible ship actions is presented on the following page. As always, use your judgment as to when these actions are appropriate.</p>\n<table class=\"table interlude-table\" style=\"width: 66%;\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Ship Board Actions</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Daytime Actions</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Work Diligently: </strong>Gain a +1 bonus on any one check for a job's daily task.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Influence: </strong>Make normal checks for a job's daily task and make an attempt to influence a single NPC (skill check based on how it is done).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sneak: </strong>Make normal checks for a job's daily task. Then make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to briefly explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shop: </strong>Take a &ndash;1 penalty on all checks for a job's daily task and visit the quartermaster's store.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shirk:</strong> Take a &ndash;1 penalty on all checks for a job's daily task and take time exploring one area of the ship. Make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to briefly explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Nighttime Actions</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sleep: </strong>Go to bed early and sleep through the night (automatically recover one level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Gamble:</strong> Play or gamble on a game of chance.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Entertain:</strong> Make one @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} to entertain the crew.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Influence:</strong> Attempt to influence a single NPC. (Skill check based on how influencing is done.)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sneak:</strong> Take time exploring one area of the ship. Make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Steal:&nbsp;</strong>Attempt to steal something from a locked door or footlocker. The character must make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} roll to avoid being seen as well as a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>Theft, Pilfering and Secrecy aboard the Wormwood</h2>\n<p>The <em>Wormwood </em>is a pirate ship, filled with dubious and murderous characters at best. Theft is common, but the key is not getting caught.</p>\n<p>To perform any action unobserved on a crowded ship use the following guidelines for modifiers to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} rolls. Remember these are guidelines&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Attempting a stealthy action in a crowd, such as casting a spell with verbal or somatic components without being noticed: &ndash;2 penalty to the roll.</p>\n<p>Attempting a stealthy action where there is a chance of discovery, such as visiting the quartermaster&rsquo;s store during work, exploring a room during the day, or attempting to open a chest in a room while its occupants are sleeping: DC 15.</p>\n<p>Attempting a stealthy action under cover of a suitable diversion, such as attempting to open lockers when the rest of the crew are working or on deck enjoying themselves: DC 10.</p>\n<p>Failing this check by 4 or less means the PC attempting the action is merely disturbed and is unable to complete the action. Failing the check by 5 or more means the PC is caught red-handed by a random crew member, and might be turned over to Master Scourge for discipline.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"MUsb5tMRBzK0Cpo1"}
{"name":"Officers of the Wormwood","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_2fzh7f9etq5","path":"Seas of Eberron#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Officers of the Wormwood</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<h2>Officers</h2>\n<h3>Captain Berrigan Redeker</h3>\n<h3>First Mate Mister Dabrak</h3>\n<p>Mr. Dabrak is the <em>Wormwood&rsquo;s</em> bullying and sadistic first mate. He is Captain Redeker&rsquo;s second-in-command, and his word is law on deck. He takes an immediate dislike to the PCs and any friends they make among the crew. Dabrak is terrified of Captain Redeker, however, and has more things on his mind than just the PCs. He&rsquo;s suspicious of everyone on the crew, and while he grows to hate the PCs, he does not sully his hands with fighting them unless they attack him, in which case he fights with relish, calling on his allies for aid in dealing with the &ldquo;mutineers.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>Dabrak is a figure to be hated, though the PCs have little opportunity to get their revenge at first. By the end of the adventure, however, the PCs finally have the opportunity to give him (and his toady, Master Scourge) their just rewards.</p>\n<h3>Master Scourge</h3>\n<p>Master Scourge is the <em>Wormwood&rsquo;s </em>boatswain and masterat-arms, and Mr. Dabrak&rsquo;s right-hand man. As boatswain, he is in charge of all activities and sailors on deck, and as master-at-arms, he is responsible for discipline. Master Scourge is a sneering man with a braided beard and a mouth full of gold teeth. His body is tall and thin, and even his long coat and heavy boots fail to give any impression of strength or bulk. A sadistic coward, Scourge uses his association with Plugg as protection and in return has no morals when it comes to the tasks his master sets. He is bold and violent when the odds are stacked in his favor, happily