{"name":"Crew of the Wormwood","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_gkbi6ipop4j","path":"Seas of Eberron Tales#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Crew of the Wormwood</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<h3>Sandara Quinn</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female human,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;helpful<br />Black</p>\n<h3>Barefoot Shamms Toppin</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;rigger,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;neutral<br />A former fisherwoman from Port Krez who never wears shoes.</p>\n<h3>Giffer Tibbs</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;neutral<br />A bedraggled dwarf with one eye.</p>\n<h3>Rosie Cusswell</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;neutral<br />Short even for a dwarf, Rosie Cusswell is fierce and has more muscles than most of the crew. She also has a fouler mouth than all the crew put together. Rosie is from Cliffscrape, and like the characters was impressed onto the&nbsp;<em>Wormwood's</em>&nbsp;crew. She has been on the ship for over a week and has already made her mark threatening others who mess with her. She has a healthy hatred of Mr. Dabrak and Scourge. She loves food, drink, and tall tales. Anyone who provides her with any of those gains a +1 bonus to any check to influence her. She is missing her fiddle, and has been unable to convince Grok to give it back to her. Any character that can recover her fiddle for her, will immediately made a firm friend of Rosie.</p>\n<h3>Tamroth Scrimshaw</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female orc,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;neutral<br />Young lass that is talented in carving scrimshaw.</p>\n<h3>\"Badger\" Stonehurler</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;uncooperative<br />An old dwarf who has his gray hear shaved into strips.</p>\n<h3>Conchobhar Turlach Dalian</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male gnome,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;rigger,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;uncooperative<br />Conchobhar Shortstone is a handsome, honey-tongued gnome who wears a foppish purple hat, an eye patch, and a white silk shirt, and carries a dandyish cane. His appearance is that of someone pretending to be a pirate, rather than a true buccaneer. Conchobhar is a professional gambler who made the mistake of drinking with the&nbsp;<em>Wormwood&rsquo;s</em>&nbsp;crew one night. He has been on ship less than 24 hours at the start of the adventure. Conchobhar is resigned to his fate but is determined to make the most of it, as he&rsquo;s always yearned for the sea anyway. One thing dominates Conchobhar&rsquo;s thinking&mdash;himself. Conchobhar is also a serial womanizer, and female characters gain a +1 bonus on all checks to influence him. He finds Rosie Cusswell magnificent.</p>\n<h3>\"Ratline\" Rattsberger</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;rigger,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;uncooperative<br />A rat-faced dwarf with slightly longer arms and three missing fingers.</p>\n<h3>Tilly Tordanthan</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;uncooperative<br />A tough joker that likes her rum.</p>\n<h3>Arzag</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male hobgoblin,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;unfriendly<br />A very tall hobgolbin ex-slaver.</p>\n<h3>Aretta Tarravan</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female half-orc,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;unfriendly<br />A bad tempered harlot whose only signs of orc heritage are big orc ears and on larger incisor.</p>\n<h3>Crimson \"Cog\" Cogward</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male human,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;unfriendly<br />Crimson Cogward (so called after the color his neck turns when he&rsquo;s angry) is a loner, and prone to incredible rages and dark moods. Cog gets pleasure from little other than combat and is quick to get into fistfights, whether because of a chance remark or simple bad luck. Cog actually volunteered to join the crew of the&nbsp;<em>Wormwood</em>. He has spent his first few days aboard stealing and secreting away goods for barter. Cog loves dark tales. A character that can succeed on telling a dark tale to Cog will gain a +1 bonus on checks to influence Cog. Characters who are fighters and favor muscle over talk, interspursing their talk with grisly details will gain a +1 bonus to influence Cog. However, a failed check is likely to elicit a violent response from the angry sailor.</p>\n<h3>Sador Chumlett</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male orc,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;unfriendly<br />A fat, pushy bully with a shaved head.</p>\n<h3>Jaundiced Sudak</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;hostile<br />A humorless, greedy mute.</p>\n<h3>Maheem</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male human,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;rigger,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;hostile<br />A big man with a permanent scowl.</p>\n<h3>Slippery Syl</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;rigger,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;hostile<br />An unhinged murderer who fled to sea to escape the gallows.</p>\n<h3>Tam \"Narwhal\" Tate</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;rigger,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;hostile<br />An old friend of Master Scourge with a large ugly nose and half an ear.</p>\n<h3>Jakes Magpie</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;swab,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;hostile<br />A thief caught stealing from the quartermaster's store and sentenced to keelhauling on the character's first day.&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"irB21HUo5OkZlAtn"}
{"name":"Officers of the Wormwood","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_gkbi6ipop4j","path":"Seas of Eberron Tales#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Officers of the Wormwood</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>This is a complete listing of all the officers aboard the&nbsp;<em>Wormwood.&nbsp;</em>Aside from Mister Dabrak, Master Scourge, Ambrose Kroop, and Grok most of the the officers that serve aboard the Wormwood should not be influenced in the beginning of the adventure. They should play little role and the characters should see them on the periphery on the ship.</p>\n<h3>Captain Berrigan \"Black Red\" Redeker</h3>\n</div>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;captain,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;hostile<br />Ruthless captain of the&nbsp;<em>Wormwood</em>.</p>\n<h3>Mister Dabrak</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female orc,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;first mate,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;hostile<br />Black Red's bullying and sadistic first mate. She is second-in-command, and her rule is law on deck. She takes an immediate dislike to the PC's and any friends they make among the crew. She is terrified of the captain, however, and has more things on her mind than the PC's. She&rsquo;s suspicious of everyone on the crew, and while he grows to hate the PCs, he does not sully his hands with fighting them unless they attack him, in which case he fights with relish, calling on his allies for aid in dealing with the &ldquo;mutineers.&rdquo; Dabrak is a figure to be hated</p>\n<h3>Master Scourge</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male half-orc,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;boatswain and master-at-arms,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> hostile</p>\n<h3>Ambrose \"Fishguts\" Kroop</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;cook,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> neutral</p>\n<h3>\"Cut-Throat\" Grok</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female half-orc,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;quartermaster,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> neutral</p>\n<h3>Grovus Stormbeard</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;artificer,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;unfriendly<br />Sailing master, storm sorcerer, and old friend of the captains.</p>\n<h3>Riaris Krine</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;master gunner,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> unfriendly</p>\n<h3>Hakrilli Quarne</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;carpenter,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span> unfriendly</p>\n<h3>Gragoth</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male orc,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;gunner's mate,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;hostile<br />Bootlicker for Dabrak and Scourge.</p>\n<h3>Patch \"Salty\"</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female dwarf,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;boatswain's mate,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;hostile<br />Sycophant of Dabrak and Scourge.</p>\n<h3>\"Caulky\" Tarroon</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Female halfling,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;cabin girl,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;uncooperative</p>\n<h3>Owlbear Hartshorn</h3>\n<p><span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Stat:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;Male orc,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Job:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;none,&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #ba372a;\"><em><strong>Intial reaction:</strong></em></span>&nbsp;neutral<br />Simplton and \"pet\" of Mr. Dabrak.</p>\n</div>","_id":"CLbre1NadVV3j2wO"}
{"name":"Ship Board Actions","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_gkbi6ipop4j","path":"Seas of Eberron Tales#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Ship Board Actions</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>In addition to their normal jobs on the ship, the PCs can also utilize their time during the day (and night) to explore the ship, scrounger for gear, interact with their shipmates, or attempt to inf luence NPCs.</p>\n<p>With the PCs potentially scattered across the ship working at their jobs, however, there is a danger that early events in the adventure might focus too much upon the actions of individual characters. Some PCs might have more time on their hands and act accordingly. To avoid this, the PCs&rsquo; activities aboard ship&mdash;carrying out their assigned tasks; exploring the ship; robbing, bullying, or befriending shipmates; working; or playing&mdash;are performed as part of ship actions. These actions ref lect the time required to set up or complete an activity, such as gathering enough crew to play a game, scouting out a room to make sure it&rsquo;s empty, and so on. Remember that even the cook&rsquo;s mate has a job to do during the day, and ship actions are meant to ref lect the available time a PC can carve out from his or her work time without going into too much detail.</p>\n<p>Each PC can normally take two ship actions each day, one during the day and one at night. A PC can also attempt to take up to two additional ship actions during the middle watch in the dead of night (any nighttime ship action marked with an asterisk), but to do so the PC must make a successful Constitution check (DC 10, +4 per extra ship action taken) or be fatigued for the next day.</p>\n<p>A list of possible ship actions is presented on the following page. As always, use your judgment as to when these actions are appropriate.</p>\n<table class=\"table interlude-table\" style=\"width: 66%;\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Ship Board Actions</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Daytime Actions</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Work Diligently: </strong>Gain a +1 bonus on any one check for a job's daily task.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Influence: </strong>Make normal checks for a job's daily task and make an attempt to influence a single NPC (skill check based on how it is done).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sneak: </strong>Make normal checks for a job's daily task. Then make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to briefly explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shop: </strong>Take a &ndash;1 penalty on all checks for a job's daily task and visit the quartermaster's store.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shirk:</strong> Take a &ndash;1 penalty on all checks for a job's daily task and take time exploring one area of the ship. Make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to briefly explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Nighttime Actions</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sleep: </strong>Go to bed early and sleep through the night (automatically recover one level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Gamble:</strong> Play or gamble on a game of chance.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Entertain:</strong> Make one @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} to entertain the crew.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Influence:</strong> Attempt to influence a single NPC. (Skill check based on how influencing is done.)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sneak:</strong> Take time exploring one area of the ship. Make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Steal:&nbsp;</strong>Attempt to steal something from a locked door or footlocker. The character must make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} roll to avoid being seen as well as a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"khaVuv8xuZkOHHB1"}
{"name":"Ship Board Entertainment","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_gkbi6ipop4j","path":"Seas of Eberron Tales#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Ship Board Entertainment</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>In addition to their normal jobs on the ship, the PCs can also utilize their time during the day (and night) to explore the ship, scrounger for gear, interact with their shipmates, or attempt to inf luence NPCs.</p>\n<p>With the PCs potentially scattered across the ship working at their jobs, however, there is a danger that early events in the adventure might focus too much upon the actions of individual characters. Some PCs might have more time on their hands and act accordingly. To avoid this, the PCs&rsquo; activities aboard ship&mdash;carrying out their assigned tasks; exploring the ship; robbing, bullying, or befriending shipmates; working; or playing&mdash;are performed as part of ship actions. These actions ref lect the time required to set up or complete an activity, such as gathering enough crew to play a game, scouting out a room to make sure it&rsquo;s empty, and so on. Remember that even the cook&rsquo;s mate has a job to do during the day, and ship actions are meant to ref lect the available time a PC can carve out from his or her work time without going into too much detail.</p>\n<p>Each PC can normally take two ship actions each day, one during the day and one at night. A PC can also attempt to take up to two additional ship actions during the middle watch in the dead of night (any nighttime ship action marked with an asterisk), but to do so the PC must make a successful Constitution check (DC 10, +4 per extra ship action taken) or be fatigued for the next day.</p>\n<p>A list of possible ship actions is presented on the following page. As always, use your judgment as to when these actions are appropriate.</p>\n<table class=\"table interlude-table\" style=\"width: 66%;\"><caption class=\"table-caption\">\n<h2 class=\"table-title\">Ship Board Actions</h2>\n</caption>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Daytime Actions</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Work Diligently: </strong>Gain a +1 bonus on any one check for a job's daily task.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Influence: </strong>Make normal checks for a job's daily task and make an attempt to influence a single NPC (skill check based on how it is done).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sneak: </strong>Make normal checks for a job's daily task. Then make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to briefly explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shop: </strong>Take a &ndash;1 penalty on all checks for a job's daily task and visit the quartermaster's store.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Shirk:</strong> Take a &ndash;1 penalty on all checks for a job's daily task and take time exploring one area of the ship. Make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to briefly explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"black-row\">\n<td>Nighttime Actions</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sleep: </strong>Go to bed early and sleep through the night (automatically recover one level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Gamble:</strong> Play or gamble on a game of chance.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Entertain:</strong> Make one @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} to entertain the crew.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Influence:</strong> Attempt to influence a single NPC. (Skill check based on how influencing is done.)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Sneak:</strong> Take time exploring one area of the ship. Make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} check to avoid detection, followed by a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Notice]{Notice} to explore one area of the ship.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Steal:&nbsp;</strong>Attempt to steal something from a locked door or footlocker. The character must make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} roll to avoid being seen as well as a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} check.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>Theft, Pilfering and Secrecy aboard the Wormwood</h2>\n<p>The <em>Wormwood </em>is a pirate ship, filled with dubious and murderous characters at best. Theft is common, but the key is not getting caught.</p>\n<p>To perform any action unobserved on a crowded ship use the following guidelines for modifiers to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} rolls. Remember these are guidelines&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Attempting a stealthy action in a crowd, such as casting a spell with verbal or somatic components without being noticed: &ndash;2 penalty to the roll.</p>\n<p>Attempting a stealthy action where there is a chance of discovery, such as visiting the quartermaster&rsquo;s store during work, exploring a room during the day, or attempting to open a chest in a room while its occupants are sleeping: DC 15.</p>\n<p>Attempting a stealthy action under cover of a suitable diversion, such as attempting to open lockers when the rest of the crew are working or on deck enjoying themselves: DC 10.</p>\n<p>Failing this check by 4 or less means the PC attempting the action is merely disturbed and is unable to complete the action. Failing the check by 5 or more means the PC is caught red-handed by a random crew member, and might be turned over to Master Scourge for discipline.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"cGf99MQmRYSnxML6"}
{"name":"Ship Entertainment","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_gkbi6ipop4j","path":"Seas of Eberron Tales#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Ship Entertainment</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>With time on their hands and precious few places to go, sailors and pirates have come up with an astonishing array of pastimes.</p>\n<h3>Songs and Stories</h3>\n<p>One way sailors amuse themselves is through songs and stories. Sailors love a good sea chantey, and characters with @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} quickly find themselves popular members of the crew. If a character succeeds at a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} check, he gains a +1 bonus per @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{raise} to social checks made to interact with any listener among the crew for the next 24 hours, up to a maximum of +4. A @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Trait Rolls]{Critical Failure}, however, indicates that the next time he attempts to use @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Performance]{Performance} to entertain the crew, everyone ignores him.</p>\n<h3>Gambling Games</h3>\n<p>Other recreations have two things in common: they are dangerous, and they are played for money. When betting on any of the following games, the minimum bet is 1 gp, and the maximum ready cash any sailor in the lesser crew is likely to have is 20 gp. Some people are bad losers&mdash;the ramifications of this are left for the GM to decide.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li><strong>Arm Wrestling:</strong> Not merely typical arm wrestling bouts, such matches are usually conducted on a barrel top covered in broken glass, knives, or caltrops. Participants make opposed @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Strength} checks, with the higher result determining the winner, and the loser taking an level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue} from @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Bumps and Bruises]{Bumps and Bruises} as his hand and arm are pushed onto whatever lies on the table.</li>\n<li><strong>Hog Lob: </strong>Participants lob a lead ingot covered in a greased piglet skin, the &ldquo;hog,&rdquo; as far across the deck as possible. This game is resolved by @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Athletics]{Athletics} checks between any number of players, who agree on a bet beforehand. The hog counts as an @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Improvised Weapons]{improvised weapon}. Some pirates claim to have participated in games played against Devourer using a live hog.</li>\n<li><strong>Heave:</strong> This potentially deadly drinking game is played with rum and takes place between any number of pirates, who bet to predict the winner beforehand. Each pirate drinks a half pint of rum in one swig. Doing so forces participants to make a successful @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} check &ndash;1 or take a level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. This check increases by &ndash;1 for each consecutive drink. Pirates then take turns drinking until only one is left standing. Some tales tell of entire crews drinking themselves to death through this game, leaving ships of drunk ghosts wandering the shipping routes.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"St0Cvtz3EoQQvW85"}
{"name":"Ship Punishments","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_gkbi6ipop4j","path":"Seas of Eberron Tales#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Ship Punishments</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>To maintain the obedience and effectiveness of their crews, most captains enforce strict schedules and shipboard laws upon their vessels, all maintained by the swift dispensation of brutal punishments. The following presents (in order of severity) the game effects of a variety of typical nautical punishments, which the PCs have the potential to face or inflict during their piratical careers. Most of these sentences are meted out just before the evening meal, at an event typically referred to as the bloody hour. Victims are tied to the whipping post on the main deck and their backs stripped for punishment&mdash;with penalties doubled for those who resist.&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Rope Bash</h3>\n<p>Little more than an admonishment&mdash;and occasionally used as a sign of endearment&mdash;a rope bash is a single attack with the hefty, sealed end of a ship&rsquo;s rope.</p>\n<h3>The Lash</h3>\n<p>This is an attack using a whip. Lashes during bloody hour is typically just cause one level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</p>\n<h3>Cat-o&rsquo;-Nine-Tails</h3>\n<p>This is an attack using a cat-o&rsquo;-ninetails, also referred to simply as a cat&mdash;lashes with the cat cause one level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}.</p>\n<h3>Confined in the Sweatbox</h3>\n<p>A cramped metal box left on deck and exposed to the sun, a sweatbox is terribly confining and replicates unbearably hot conditions. Each four hours in the sweatbox the victim must make a @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Traits]{Vigor} at &ndash;1 for each 8 hours they spend in the sweat box, or suffer a level of @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-rules.Fatigue]{Fatigue}. Any creature with fire resistance is immune to the effects of the sweatbox. Victims typically spend 8, 12 or even 24 hours locked up in the sweatbox.</p>\n<h3>Keelhauling</h3>\n<p>The most frightful of pirate punishments is keelhauling, as it generally ends in death&mdash;often by decapitation. Being keelhauled involves being tied to a rope looped over a ship&rsquo;s keel and dragged down one side of a ship, underwater across the barnacle encrusted hull, and up the other side. Keelhauling can be done either fast or slow. If done fast, the barnacles cut deep and flense the victim, dealing 2d6 points of damage per round. If done slow, shallower cuts are incurred, dealing 1d6 damage per round, but the risk of drowning increases. How long keelhauling takes typically depends on the vessel, with a keelhauling on a ship like the Wormwood taking 6 rounds if done fast and 12 rounds if done slow.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"xMoJCYS3QhlKtV09"}
{"name":"Ship Roles","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_gkbi6ipop4j","path":"Seas of Eberron Tales#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Ship Roles</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>All crew members on any ship have specific roles and responsibilities, often with harsh punishments being meted out upon those who shirk their duties. Listed here are some of the standard roles aboard a typical ship. Not all of these roles might be represented on every vessel, but such details can help players understand their characters&rsquo; daily duties.</p>\n<h3>Artificer/Mage</h3>\n<p>Many ships that ply the waters around Khorvaire have an artificer or mage on board. They can be responsible for the functioning of any magical locomotion of the ship, repairs, general arcane knowledge or any number of other magical needs the ship might have. They are also expected to contribute firepower to any ship to ship conflicts that happen on the vessel.&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Boatswain</h3>\n<p>The boatswain, or bosun (pronounced &ldquo;bosun&rdquo; either way), is responsible for the upper deck of the vessel and above. This makes the boatswain accountable for all rope, rigging, anchors, and sails. At the start of the day, the boatswain and those under her weigh anchor, raise the sails and report on the general condition of the ship&rsquo;s deck to the captain. As she oversees many of the ship&rsquo;s basic daily labors, the boatswain is often responsible for keeping discipline and dispensing punishment.</p>\n<h3>Cabin Boy/Girl</h3>\n<p>Servant to the captain and other officers, this low-ranking and typically young crew member assists other sailors in their duties and runs various errands across the ship, requiring him or her to gain a measure of understanding of almost all the ship&rsquo;s roles.</p>\n<h3>Captain</h3>\n<p>The ultimate authority on any ship, his word is law to all on board. The captain chooses where to sail, what are fitting punishments for breeches in discipline,&nbsp; and who fills the other stations aboard the vessel, among many other command decisions. Leadership can prove perilous, however, as a captain is, above all, meant to secure success for his ship and crew. Failing to do so increases the threat of mutiny.</p>\n<h3>Carpenter</h3>\n<p>No matter what enchantments or alchemical unguents augment a pirate ship, its heart and bones are still wood. This simple fact makes the carpenter one of the most important positions aboard any vessel. Carpenters are chief ly responsible for maintaining the ship below the deck, finding and plugging leaks, repairing damage, and replacing masts and yards.</p>\n<h3>Cook</h3>\n<p>While the quartermaster normally allocates the rations, the cook and his apprentices make and distribute meals to the crew. Although some better-outfitted vessels employ skilled cooks to attend to the captain and the officers, many cooks are drawn from crew members who have suffered crippling injuries, allowing them to still serve even after such trauma.</p>\n<h3>Healer</h3>\n<p>Many ships have a healer on board to tend to any injuries that happen. Whether this is a House Jorasco healer, Jorasco trained, or some herbalist with slight training in healing, depends on the vessel.</p>\n<h3>Master-at-Arms</h3>\n<p>Concerned with the security of the ship, the fitness of the crew, and the dispensing of justice, the master-at-arms typically is one of the most feared and dreaded of a ship&rsquo;s officers.</p>\n<h3>Master Gunner</h3>\n<p>The master gunner is in charge of all shipboard artillery, ensuring the weapons are kept in good working order and that the crew knows how to use them. She maintains the ballistas, catapults, and so on.</p>\n<h3>Quartermaster</h3>\n<p>The quartermaster oversees the supplies and items stored aboard the ship. She maintains the supplies of food and weaponry, oversees the disbursement of food to the cook, and doles out the rum ration to the crew.</p>\n<h3>Rigger</h3>\n<p>Riggers work the rigging and unfurl the sails. In battle, next to that of a boarding party, the riggers&rsquo; job is one of the most dangerous, as they pull enemy vessels near enough to board.</p>\n<h3>Swab</h3>\n<p>Any sailor who mops the decks. Also used as slang for any low-ranking or unskilled crew member.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"4WhIpeBOuB8BqSfp"}
{"name":"Theft, Pilfering, and Secrecy","permission":{"default":0,"DX8acFfCTTwwzgWq":3},"flags":{"journal-links":{"references":{}},"cf":{"id":"temp_gkbi6ipop4j","path":"Seas of Eberron Tales#/CF_SEP/The Wormwood","color":"#000000"}},"content":"<div class=\"swade-core savage-eberron-core\">\n<div class=\"section-header\">\n<h1>Theft, Pilfering, and Secrecy</h1>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p>The <em>Wormwood </em>is a pirate ship, filled with dubious and murderous characters at best. Theft is common, but the key is not getting caught.</p>\n<p>To perform any action unobserved on a crowded ship use the following guidelines for modifiers to @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Stealth]{Stealth} and @Compendium[swade-core-rules.swade-skills.Thievery]{Thievery} rolls.</p>\n<ul class=\"red-bullet-list\">\n<li>Attempting a stealthy action in a crowd, such as casting a spell with verbal or somatic components without being noticed: &ndash;3 penalty to the roll.</li>\n<li>Attempting a stealthy action where there is a chance of discovery, such as visiting the quartermaster&rsquo;s store during work, exploring a room during the day, or attempting to open a chest in a room while its occupants are sleeping: &ndash;2 penalty to the roll.</li>\n<li>Attempting a stealthy action under cover of a suitable diversion, such as attempting to open lockers when the rest of the crew are working or on deck enjoying themselves: no modifier.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Failure</h3>\n<p>Failing this check means the character attempting the action is merely disturbed and is unable to complete the action. A Critical Failure on the checkthe character is caught red-handed by a random crew member, and might be turned over to Master Scourge for discipline.</p>\n</div>\n</div>","_id":"FGK7pnktoB6gSts3"}
